eanmarie.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and English: variant of   Roman  ."]}]},{"name":"Quintin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Yves, Andre, Dominique, Gilles, Lucien, Michel, Oliva, Roch.","Breton: from the personal name <i>Quintin</i>, which is of the same Latin origin as 2 below, but also considered a derivative of Old Breton <i>kint</i> ‘first’.","French; Spanish (<b>Quintín</b>): from the personal name <i>Quintin</i> (Spanish <i>Quintín</i>), from Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a Christian saint's name (see   Quentin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Quinton","meanings":["English: from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Quentin</i>, <i>Quintin</i> (Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a suffixed form of <i>quintus</i> ‘fifth’), popular in France from the cult of Saint Quentin of Amiens, and brought to England by the Normans. The surname was altered to <i>Quinton</i> by association with the placenames in 2 below.","English: habitational name from from any of three places called Quinton (Gloucestershire, Northamptonshire, Worcestershire) or from Quainton (Buckinghamshire). The placenames probably derive from Old English <i>cwēn</i> ‘queen’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or perhaps from Old English <i>cwene</i> ‘woman’ + <i>tūn</i> or an Old English personal name <i>Cwēna</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Saint-Quentin (Manche) in France or possibly from Saint-Quentin-en-Tourmont (Somme), the site of the martyrdom of Saint Quentin of Amiens, a 3rd-century Roman missionary to Gaul. It is not certain that this surname survived into the modern period."]},{"name":"Quentin","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Quentin</i> (from Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a suffixed form of <i>quintus</i> ‘fifth’), popular in France from the cult of Saint Quentin of Amiens, a 3rd-century Roman missionary to Gaul. Compare   Quintin  .","English: variant of   Quinton  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":46,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":119,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"John de St. Quintin was born about 1336, in Yorkshire, England as the son of Sir John St Quinton and Agnes Herbert. He married Elizabeth de Swinhoe about 1360. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"